THE telecommunication services have continued penetrating in the country, with the increase of the number of registered sim cards by 4.5 per cent in the past one year. The number of registered sim card reached 55,365,239 million by April this year as compared to 52,965,816 million by April 2021. Speaking during the tabling of the budget estimates of the Ministry of Information, Communication and Information Technology on Friday in Dodoma, Minister Nape Nnauye said the increased registered simcards will expand the telecom services in the country and enable Tanzanians access mobile services more. The Minister also said the number of internet users has gone up from 29.1million in April 2021 to 29.9 million in April 2022, equivalent to an increase of 2.7 per cent. On top of that, the minister said the number of phone users who use mobile transactions has also gone up by 30.8 per cent from 27milion users in April 2021 to 35 million during the period this year. Furthermore, based on media, Mr Nnauye said the number of cable Television has increased from 40 in April 2021 to 59 the same month in 2022 equivalent to a percentage increase of 47.5. “The number of the newspapers has increased from 272 and reached 284 in April 2022 equivalent to an increase of 4.4 per cent,” the minister said. Moreover, Mr Nnauye said, so far the number of radio broadcast stations has increased from 200 stations in 2021 to 210 in April 2022 equivalent to a 5 per cent increase while Television broadcasting stations have increased from 50 stations in 2021 to 56 on the same month in 2022 equivalent to 12 per cent. The Minister said the government has continued to create a conducive environment for the users of the technology and broadcasting particularly online content which has contributed to the increase of the employment opportunities among youths. “By April 2022 online television has increased from 552 to 663 equivalent to an increase of 20.1 per cent, blogs have increased from 134 to 148 equivalent to an increase of 10.4 per cent and online radio has increased from 25 up to 27 equal to 8 per cent,” Mr Nnauye said.